Here is the strict, command-level audit of the Bazzite AI Smart Home Architecture Draft (v4).

This plan is highly advanced and demonstrates excellent domain knowledge—specifically regarding ROCm hardware-level bugs on the 780M (Flash Attention, MES hangs) and Docker network topologies bypassing bridge isolation. However, bridging the gap between conceptual architecture and beginner-safe execution requires resolving several critical syntax shortcuts, file-permission traps, and minor security oversights.

🚨 ISSUE CLASSIFICATION & REMEDIATION
CRITICAL ISSUES (Will break execution or cause system crash)

Docker Volume Ownership Trap (EX.2 mcpo):

Issue: You specify user: "<UID>:<GID>" for the mcpo container to read Nextcloud data. However, you also mount ./memory:/app/memory. When Docker Compose maps a host directory that doesn't exist yet, the Docker daemon creates it as root:root. When mcpo starts as the Nextcloud UID, it will crash with Permission Denied because it cannot write to its own memory store.

Fix: You must explicitly create and take ownership of the directory before running docker compose up.

Command: mkdir -p ~/docker/mcpo/memory && sudo chown <UID>:<GID> ~/docker/mcpo/memory

Numeric UID/GID Retrieval (EX.0.g):

Issue: The command ls -la /var/srv/nextcloud/data will return string names (e.g., www-data www-data) if the host recognizes the user ID. Docker Compose requires strictly numeric IDs in the user: directive if the container does not have a matching user string.

Fix: Use ls -ln /var/srv/nextcloud/data. The -n flag forces numeric output (e.g., 33 33).

Pseudo-code YAML Syntax (EX.1 & EX.2):

Issue: The draft uses shorthand YAML (e.g., devices: /dev/kfd, /dev/dri and environment: HSA_OVERRIDE_GFX_VERSION, OLLAMA_FLASH_ATTENTION=false). If a beginner copies this, docker compose up will instantly fail with YAML parsing errors.

Fix: Use strict YAML lists and key-value pairs.

Correct Syntax:

code
Yaml
download
content_copy
expand_less
devices:
  - /dev/kfd:/dev/kfd
  - /dev/dri:/dev/dri
environment:
  - HSA_OVERRIDE_GFX_VERSION=11.0.2
  - OLLAMA_FLASH_ATTENTION=false
MAJOR ISSUES (Security, Instability, or Misconfigurations)

Unnecessary API Exposure on LAN (EX.1 & EX.4):

Issue: Mapping 11434:11434 (Ollama), 10300:10300 (Whisper), and 10200:10200 (Piper) defaults to binding on 0.0.0.0. This exposes unauthenticated AI and voice endpoints to every device on the LAN.

Fix: Because Home Assistant is on network_mode: host, it shares the host's loopback interface. You can bind these ports strictly to localhost.

Compose Fix: ports: - "127.0.0.1:11434:11434"

HA Setup Fix (EX.4/EX.5): Instruct HA to connect to http://127.0.0.1:11434 instead of <LAN-IP>:11434. (Open WebUI remains unaffected; it communicates via the ai-net internal Docker bridge as http://ollama:11434).

Missing Persistent Data Directories in Wyoming Compose (EX.4):

Issue: Models download at runtime. While the volumes: block is listed, the default rhasspy/wyoming-* containers require explicit flags to know where to save them, otherwise they pull the ~150MB models into ephemeral container space on every restart.

Fix: Update commands to include the data directory: --data-dir /data.

MINOR ISSUES (Clarity & Efficiency)

Free Memory Command Output (EX.0.e):

Issue: free -h | awk '/^Mem:/{print $7}' technically prints the "available" column, not the "free" column.

Fix: Update documentation text to state "Verify available RAM" rather than "free RAM" to align with Linux memory management principles.

Home Assistant Container Image (EX.3):

Issue: lscr.io/linuxserver/homeassistant is used instead of the official ghcr.io/home-assistant/home-assistant:stable. LSIO requires PUID/PGID variables, whereas the official image runs root-native (standard for network_mode: host smart home hubs).

Fix: Either image is acceptable, but using the official image eliminates the need for PUID/PGID variables, reducing configuration overhead.

📋 ELEMENT CLASSIFICATION

ESSENTIAL: amdgpu.noretry=0 kernel argument and HSA_OVERRIDE_GFX_VERSION=11.0.2. Do not alter. Without these, the AMD 780M will hard-lock the OS under compute loads.

ESSENTIAL: network_mode: host for Home Assistant. Required for mDNS (local device discovery).

ESSENTIAL: Rejecting Docker/System command execution tools for the AI. Security posture evaluation here is 100% correct.

OPTIONAL: The mcpo filesystem/Nextcloud integration. Excellent capability, but not strictly required for base AI/Voice functionality.

UNNECESSARY: Sections EX.7, EX.8, and EX.9 placeholder texts. If they are not procedurally covered, they should be removed from the deployment manual to reduce cognitive load, keeping the document strictly focused on EX.0-EX.6.

